ooked":"<p>Then the only thing i would change is i would have the motor relative encoders report back in post-gearbox rotations, which would require you to change the RobotMath functions to ignore it and that might be it</p>","post_number":13,"post_type":1,"posts_count":20,"updated_at":"2025-02-07T16:21:59.183Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":9,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":129,"readers_count":128,"score":45.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":485544,"topic_slug":"maxmotion-elevator-tuning","display_username":"","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":57833,"username":"hjmcphail76","name":"Harrison","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/hjmcphail76/{size}/234713_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":51887,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"YAGSL & YASS Creator "},"post_url":"/t/maxmotion-elevator-tuning/485544/13","custom_user_title":"YAGSL & YASS Creator ","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3505103,"name":"Luca Carvalho","username":"CarvalhoJeo","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/carvalhojeo/{size}/249007_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-07T16:24:10.123Z","cooked":"<p>As <a class="mention" href="/u/nstrike">@nstrike</a> mentioned, in their code, they used the ElevatorFeedforward class to calculate the feedforward and then pass it to the setReference() method.</p>
<p>This thread discusses the same topic—I believe there’s a lot of confusion around this:</p>
<aside class="quote quote-modified" data-post="1" data-topic="479978">
  <div class="title">
    <div class="quote-controls"></div>
    <img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/e8c25b/48.png" class="avatar">
    <a href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/t/how-to-use-max-motion-with-feedforward/479978">How to use Max Motion with Feedforward</a> <a class="badge-category__wrapper " href="/c/technical/programming/30"><span data-category-id="30" style="--category-badge-color: #F7941D; --category-badge-text-color: #FFF; --parent-category-badge-color: #3AB54A;" data-parent-category-id="9" data-drop-close="true" class="badge-category --has-parent" title="Discussion of any ideas, algorithms, etc."><span class="badge-category__name">Programming</span></span></a>
  </div>
  <blockquote>
    I’ve been looking at the new REVLib API and noticed that even though they implemented a trapezoidal motion profile that uses position control, the only feedforward you can input into the config is Kf which is just Kv from what I’ve read. Even further, they discourage you from using their “kF” entirely when using MAXMotion: 
 <a class="lightbox" href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/original/3X/3/d/3d621480f03f723fadd211f68a50b857113d0fe6.png" data-download-href="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/uploads/default/3d621480f03f723fadd211f68a50b857113d0fe6" title="image">[image]</a> 
On top of this, they don’t expose the velocity and acceleration setpoints in the API, meaning you can’t calculate the feedforward on the RIO. And even if you could,…
  </blockquote>
</aside>
